## Infrastructure Vulnerabilities and Adaptation Challenges

### Resilience of Infrastructure in Developed Countries

Developed countries generally have more robust infrastructure compared to developing nations, but climate change still poses significant risks. Infrastructure such as roads, bridges, and energy systems are designed to withstand historical weather extremes, which are becoming increasingly inadequate due to the intensification of extreme weather events. For example, the Northern Midwest of the United States experienced record-breaking flooding in recent years, with Nebraska alone facing $439 million in infrastructure damage ([Thomasnet, 2020](https://www.thomasnet.com/insights/how-does-climate-change-impact-the-supply-chain/)).

While developed countries often have greater financial and technical capacity to maintain and upgrade infrastructure, the increasing frequency of extreme events demands more frequent and costly adaptations. The economic cost of maintaining infrastructure resilience is significant, but necessary to avoid greater losses from infrastructure failure.

### Adaptation Efforts and Economic Costs

Adaptation to climate change in developed countries involves upgrading infrastructure to withstand more severe weather, investing in early warning systems, and implementing policies to reduce vulnerability. The economics of adaptation indicate that while adaptation can be costly, it is often less expensive than the costs of inaction. For example, the World Bank estimates global adaptation costs to be between $70 billion and $100 billion annually by 2050 to manage a 2°C warmer world, with developed countries bearing a substantial share of these costs due to their economic size and infrastructure complexity ([World Bank, 2010](https://openknowledge.worldbank.org/handle/10986/12750)).

