## Comparative Vulnerability and Outlook

### Relative Impact Compared to Developing Countries

Developed countries generally fare better than developing countries in terms of climate vulnerability due to higher adaptive capacity, diversified economies, and stronger institutions. For example, the UK, as a higher latitude country, is expected to experience less severe climate impacts compared to tropical developing nations. Nonetheless, developed countries face significant challenges related to economic costs, infrastructure resilience, and social equity ([Schroders, 2015](https://www.schroders.com/en/ch/asset-management/insights/economics/climate-change-and-the-global-economy-regional-effects/)).

### Long-Term Economic and Social Risks

Despite their advantages, developed countries are not immune to the long-term risks posed by climate change. Persistent extreme weather, sea-level rise, and supply chain disruptions could lead to sustained economic losses and social challenges. Proactive and sustained investment in mitigation and adaptation is essential to minimize these risks and ensure economic stability.

