## Conclusion

Developed countries face multifaceted challenges from climate change that affect their economies, infrastructure, public health, and fiscal stability. While they possess greater adaptive capacity than developing nations, the increasing frequency and severity of climate-related events necessitate substantial investments in mitigation and adaptation. The economic costs of inaction are likely to exceed those of proactive measures, underscoring the importance of integrating climate resilience into national planning and policy frameworks.

Moreover, the interconnectedness of the global economy means that climate change impacts in other regions can indirectly affect developed countries through trade and supply chains. Therefore, international cooperation and support for global climate action remain critical.

In summary, climate change poses significant but manageable risks to developed countries, provided that they commit to sustained and coordinated efforts to reduce emissions and enhance resilience.

